74
00:06:54,914 --> 00:06:58,918
Do you think there's any chance
we'll get back together?

75
00:06:58,953 --> 00:07:02,189
I don't think so, Ben.

76
00:07:02,224 --> 00:07:05,425
I think it ran its course.

77
00:07:06,926 --> 00:07:08,928
Besides,
I'm with Steve now.

78
00:07:11,431 --> 00:07:13,933
Have you
slept with him?

79
00:07:15,435 --> 00:07:16,436
Yes.

80
00:07:20,440 --> 00:07:23,443
Was it good?
I mean, is it better than...

81
00:07:23,478 --> 00:07:26,446
I don't wanna talk
about it with you, Ben

82
00:07:26,481 --> 00:07:29,449
I've gotta go.
Sorry, Ben.

83
00:07:29,949 --> 00:07:31,951
Suzy?

84
00:09:20,059 --> 00:09:23,027
To think about her now
with someone else,

85
00:09:23,062 --> 00:09:26,065
It felt like all the oxygen
had been sucked from the room.

86
00:10:28,127 --> 00:10:32,131
After my breakup with Suzy, I
just couldn't fall asleep anymore.

87
00:10:32,166 --> 00:10:36,636
The more I tried to sleep,
the less tired I felt.

88
00:10:36,671 --> 00:10:39,156
I was wide awake.

89
00:10:39,191 --> 00:10:41,606
I tried everything.

90
00:10:41,641 --> 00:10:45,144
I'd just become
immune to sleep.

91
00:10:47,146 --> 00:10:50,149
I suddenly found
I had eight extra hours.

92
00:10:51,651 --> 00:10:54,987
My life had been
extended by a third.

93
00:10:55,488 --> 00:10:57,990
I wanted time to pass quickly,
but instead I was forced to witness

94
00:10:58,025 --> 00:11:00,993
The passing of every
second of every hour.

95
00:11:03,496 --> 00:11:05,998
I wanted the hurt I felt
to go away.

96
00:11:06,033 --> 00:11:08,518
But in some cruel trick
of events,

97
00:11:08,553 --> 00:11:11,003
I now had even more time
on my hands.

98
00:11:11,038 --> 00:11:14,472
More time
to think about Suzy.

99
00:11:14,507 --> 00:11:18,010
Would you mind getting out
Just checking that wheel?

100
00:11:32,024 --> 00:11:35,993
I took the bus
with no real place to go.

101
00:11:36,028 --> 00:11:41,033
I watched the landscape slowly change as
it clung to the last hours of sunlight,

102
00:11:41,534 --> 00:11:44,537
Before leaving me to get
another sleepless night.

103
00:11:57,550 --> 00:12:01,554
I started to read all the books
I wished I'd had time to read.

104
00:12:01,589 --> 00:12:05,558
With the extra hours, I even had
time to reread my favorite ones.

105
00:12:17,069 --> 00:12:19,071
But she was never far
from my mind.

106
00:13:41,654 --> 00:13:44,156
Two pounds 75, please.

107
00:13:51,163 --> 00:13:55,167
Ah, how much is it without these two?

108
00:14:02,675 --> 00:14:03,676
One pound 70.

109
00:14:11,183 --> 00:14:15,187
It was getting obvious that I
needed to trade some of my time.

110
00:14:21,193 --> 00:14:23,696
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

111
00:14:25,698 --> 00:14:27,700
Yeah, yeah.

112
00:14:27,735 --> 00:14:29,667
Yeah. Yeah.

113
00:14:29,702 --> 00:14:33,706
Mmm, mmm, mmm.
It all looks fantastic, man.

114
00:14:35,207 --> 00:14:37,209
I think you'll fit in
very well here.

115
00:14:40,212 --> 00:14:42,214
It's a great
feeling inside, Ben.

116
00:14:45,217 --> 00:14:47,469
It's marvelous. We hope
you've enjoyed reading about.

117
00:14:47,504 --> 00:14:49,722
What it's like to be part
of Sainsbury's and listening

118
00:14:49,757 --> 00:14:51,223
I know, I've been
through this with you.

119
00:14:51,724 --> 00:14:56,228
There's so many opportunities,
Ben. It's a life thing.

120
00:15:02,234 --> 00:15:05,738
I could feel a faint shift
in a faraway place.

121
00:15:07,740 --> 00:15:11,994
A current of unknown
consequences was on its way

122
00:15:12,029 --> 00:15:16,248
Moving towards me like
an unstoppable wave of fate.

123
00:15:18,250 --> 00:15:21,754
T-E-A-M-W-O-R-K. Work.

124
00:15:22,254 --> 00:15:24,256
Teamwork, Ben.

125
00:15:25,257 --> 00:15:27,259
Welcome aboard.

126
00:15:46,278 --> 00:15:49,782
And so I started working
the night shift at Sainsbury's

127
00:15:51,784 --> 00:15:54,286
During the hours most
normal people are sleeping,

128
00:15:54,321 --> 00:15:56,754
I'm busy trading my time.

129
00:15:56,789 --> 00:16:00,793
I give them my extra eight hours,
and they give me money. Cash back.

130
00:16:08,550 --> 00:16:11,518
- Hi.
- Oh, hi.

131
00:16:11,553 --> 00:16:16,058
I'm late again. Jenkins is
gonna kill me. See you later.

132
00:16:16,093 --> 00:16:17,524
Yeah, see ya.

133
00:16:17,559 --> 00:16:21,028
- Sharon!
- Yes, Mr. Jenkins?

134
00:16:21,063 --> 00:16:23,315
- Late again, Sharon.
- I'm sorry, Mr. Jenkins

135
00:16:23,350 --> 00:16:25,567
- Second time this week.
- I know, Mr. Jenkins.

136
00:16:25,602 --> 00:16:28,070
I'm sorry,
it won't happen again.

137
00:16:28,570 --> 00:16:29,071
Ay.
Ok

138
00:16:39,365 --> 00:16:43,334
My first year at art college
was boring to say the least.

139
00:16:43,369 --> 00:16:46,372
But it helped me to appreciate
the fundamentals of still life.

140
00:16:46,872 --> 00:16:49,375
I'd like to remind the custome
that there's a special

141
00:16:49,410 --> 00:16:52,843
Two for the price of one
offer on aisle ten.

142
00:16:52,878 --> 00:16:57,883
Fresh bread and cakes. That's aisle ten for
a special two for the price of one offer.

143
00:17:01,387 --> 00:17:03,889
Well, don't just stare at it, Ben

144
00:17:05,391 --> 00:17:06,392
Clean it up.

145
00:17:13,899 --> 00:17:16,902
You see, I've always
wanted to be a painter.

146
00:17:17,403 --> 00:17:19,370
And like many artists
before me,

147
00:17:19,405 --> 00:17:22,408
The female form has always been
a great source of inspiration.

148
00:17:28,914 --> 00:17:31,917
I've always been in awe of the
power they unknowingly possess.

149
00:17:35,921 --> 00:17:38,924
Now, are you going
to clean them up or not?

150
00:17:46,932 --> 00:17:50,401
There is an art to dealing with
the boredom of an eight-hour shift.

151
00:17:50,436 --> 00:17:53,939
An art to putting your mind somewhere
else while the seconds slowly tick away.

152
00:17:55,441 --> 00:17:57,693
I found that all
the people working here

153
00:17:57,728 --> 00:17:59,945
Had perfected
their own individual art.

154
00:17:59,980 --> 00:18:01,912
Take Sharon Pintey.

155
00:18:01,947 --> 00:18:05,451
Sharon knows rule number one.
The clock is the enemy.

156
00:18:05,486 --> 00:18:07,418
The basic rule is this:

157
00:18:07,453 --> 00:18:11,957
The more you look at the clock,
the slower the time goes.

158
00:18:17,963 --> 00:18:19,965
It will uncover
the hiding place of your mind

159
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:22,468
And torture it
with every second.

160
00:18:27,973 --> 00:18:30,976
This is the basic art in dealing
with the trade of your time.

161
00:18:35,981 --> 00:18:37,483
Any cash back?

162
00:18:56,001 --> 00:18:58,969
This is Barry Brickman.

163
00:18:59,004 --> 00:19:02,508
You see, Barry thinks of himself
as a bit of a daredevil stuntman.

164
00:19:04,510 --> 00:19:07,204
For a start,
Barry is quite well-Known.

165
00:19:07,239 --> 00:19:09,898
When one of Barry's
bike tricks went wrong,

166
00:19:10,399 --> 00:19:12,317
The cameraman put it
on the internet.

167
00:19:14,236 --> 00:19:16,238
Barry has stuck
to his scooter ever since.

168
00:19:18,740 --> 00:19:20,742
Matt Stephens is also
a king scooterer.

169
00:19:26,248 --> 00:19:28,750
And what was
the other thing?

170
00:19:33,755 --> 00:19:36,758
And what was
the other thing?

171
00:19:36,793 --> 00:19:40,262
- Sausage!
- Oh, yeah.

172
00:19:43,765 --> 00:19:46,268
Now Barry and Matt
are good friends.

173
00:19:46,303 --> 00:19:48,235
There you go.
Take care.

174
00:19:48,270 --> 00:19:50,772
Between them, they have come
up with a very different way

175
00:19:50,807 --> 00:19:53,775
Of dealing with
the trade of their time.

176
00:19:53,810 --> 00:19:55,277
Look. Look.

177
00:19:57,279 --> 00:20:01,783
Theirs is an art to finding
anything to do that isn't work.

178
00:20:10,792 --> 00:20:14,045
A few days later,
Barry and Matt were reported

179
00:20:14,080 --> 00:20:17,299
For what they called
"helping the ladies."

180
00:20:18,800 --> 00:20:22,304
It was these shampoo bottles
that sent them on their quest.

181
00:20:22,339 --> 00:20:24,271
Barry and Matt knew
what they looked like.

182
00:20:24,306 --> 00:20:27,309
And they knew that the women in the
supermarket knew what they looked like.

183
00:20:27,344 --> 00:20:29,811
Their theory was that even
though it was a sex toy

184
00:20:30,312 --> 00:20:32,063
Masquerading as
a bottle of shampoo,

185
00:20:32,098 --> 00:20:33,780
Women would like
to try it as a sex toy

186
00:20:33,815 --> 00:20:37,284
But were embarrassed to buy it
because they knew what it looked like.

187
00:20:37,319 --> 00:20:42,324
The decision to buy it would be an easier
one if they were already at the checkout.

188
00:20:42,359 --> 00:20:44,826
If they didn't object,
then Barry and Matt knew

189
00:20:44,861 --> 00:20:48,830
They'd helped a bottle
find a happy home.

190
00:20:52,751 --> 00:20:54,718
Barry had challenged Matt
to a scooter race

191
00:20:54,753 --> 00:20:57,221
In which they would sprint
down one aisle and up the next.

192
00:20:57,256 --> 00:21:00,509
They would do all 14 aisles, and
then back to the starting line.

193
00:21:00,544 --> 00:21:03,727
They had been waiting for the
day the manager called in sick.

194
00:21:03,762 --> 00:21:08,767
The art of doing something else other than
the work you're supposed to do, is addictive.

195
00:21:08,802 --> 00:21:10,769
The excitement of doing something
that you shouldn't be doing,

196
00:21:10,804 --> 00:21:13,237
Along with the consequences
if you're caught doing it,

197
00:21:13,272 --> 00:21:16,275
Are so strong that it often pulls
others away from their own art.

198
00:21:16,310 --> 00:21:20,279
On your marks,
get set, go!

199
00:21:28,787 --> 00:21:30,289
We got winded!

200
00:21:40,465 --> 00:21:43,468
I hadn't slept in two weeks.

201
00:21:47,973 --> 00:21:52,477
My breakup with Suzy had left me with
a sense that time had become unhinged.

202
00:21:52,512 --> 00:21:55,247
I drifted between
imagination and reality,

203
00:21:55,282 --> 00:21:57,983
Between past and present
with increasing ease.

204
00:22:00,485 --> 00:22:02,988
I feel like a real man.
You like men.

205
00:22:03,023 --> 00:22:05,007
You like real men,
don't you?

206
00:22:05,042 --> 00:22:07,518
When I'm out there in the kit

207
00:22:07,553 --> 00:22:09,960
On the pitch
with the boys,

208
00:22:09,995 --> 00:22:13,498
I look like a god,
I'm an adonis.

209
00:22:26,511 --> 00:22:30,515
I keep myself
in good shape.

210
00:22:30,550 --> 00:22:34,484
I see the looks.
I ignore them.

211
00:22:34,519 --> 00:22:38,023
I feel the bolts of time slowly
coming away from the breakup.

212
00:22:38,058 --> 00:22:40,525
Time manipulation
is not a precise science.

213
00:22:41,026 --> 00:22:43,778
Like any art, it's
personal to the individual

214
00:22:43,813 --> 00:22:46,531
So what is the art in making
my shift go so fast?

215
00:22:52,037 --> 00:22:54,039
I imagine the opposite.

216
00:22:54,539 --> 00:22:57,007
That time is frozen.

217
00:22:57,042 --> 00:23:01,546
I imagine the remote control
for life has been paused.

218
00:23:34,079 --> 00:23:37,582
Within this frozen world, I'm
able to walk freely and unnoticed.

219
00:23:41,086 --> 00:23:43,588
Nobody would even know
that time had stopped.

220
00:23:51,096 --> 00:23:53,063
And when it started
back up again,

221
00:23:53,098 --> 00:23:56,101
The invisible join would be
seamless except for a slight shudder.

222
00:23:57,602 --> 00:24:00,605
Not unlike the feeling of
somebody walking over your grave.

223
00:24:12,617 --> 00:24:16,371
That moment when you see someone
walking down the street

224
00:24:16,406 --> 00:24:20,125
Who is so beautiful
you just can't help but stare.

225
00:24:22,627 --> 00:24:25,130
Well, imagine as I do,
that with the world on pause

226
00:24:25,630 --> 00:24:28,133
It becomes very easy to
understand the concept of beauty.

227
00:24:29,634 --> 00:24:32,137
To have it frozen
in front of you.

228
00:24:32,172 --> 00:24:33,138
Captured.

229
00:24:35,640 --> 00:24:37,142
Unaware.

230
00:24:48,153 --> 00:24:51,621
For me, this fascination with
beauty started at a very young age.

231
00:24:51,656 --> 00:24:56,161
I was six or seven, and my mom and
dad had taken on a foreign student.

232
00:24:56,196 --> 00:24:57,627
She was in her late teens,

233
00:24:57,662 --> 00:25:00,630
And was studying English
at a nearby school.

234
00:25:00,665 --> 00:25:04,669
Being swedish, the walk from the shower
to her room didn't need to be a modest one

235
00:25:06,671 --> 00:25:11,676
It was at that moment that something
very profound happened to me.

236
00:25:11,711 --> 00:25:16,681
I was exposed to the female form
in a way I had never experienced.

237
00:25:16,716 --> 00:25:21,151
I felt fascination and wonder
at the beauty of her nakedness.

238
00:25:21,186 --> 00:25:24,689
And I wanted to freeze the world so that
i could live in that moment for a week.

239
00:25:26,191 --> 00:25:30,160
I have never had a feeling
of such completeness.

240
00:25:30,195 --> 00:25:33,698
To this day I still think it was one of
the most beautiful things I have ever seen.

241
00:25:43,208 --> 00:25:45,210
[knocking]

242
00:25:51,216 --> 00:25:52,717
